### Stricli CLI Application Setup (app.ts)

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/packages/create-app/tests/baselines/reference/app/creates new application/multi-command/module [default]/package properties/custom metadata.txt

Builds the main Stricli application by defining routes and application metadata. It utilizes `@stricli/core` for route mapping and application building, and `@stricli/auto-complete` for generating shell completion commands.

```typescript
import { buildApplication, buildRouteMap } from "@stricli/core";
import { buildInstallCommand, buildUninstallCommand } from "@stricli/auto-complete";
import { name, version, description } from "../package.json";
import { subdirCommand } from "./commands/subdir/command";
import { nestedRoutes } from "./commands/nested/commands";

const routes = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        subdir: subdirCommand,
        nested: nestedRoutes,
        install: buildInstallCommand("test", { bash: "__test_bash_complete" }),
        uninstall: buildUninstallCommand("test", { bash: true }),
    },
    docs: {
        brief: description,
        hideRoute: {
            install: true,
            uninstall: true,
        },
    },
});

export const app = buildApplication(routes, {
    name,
    versionInfo: {
        currentVersion: version,
    },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Organize Commands Hierarchically with Route Maps

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Illustrates the use of `buildRouteMap` to create nested command structures and manage aliases. This function allows for organizing commands into logical groups, improving CLI navigation and offering shorthand command invocation.

```typescript
import { buildRouteMap, buildCommand, numberParser } from "@stricli/core";

// Helper function to create math commands
function buildUnaryMathCommand(op: "log" | "sqrt") {
    return buildCommand({
        func: (flags: {}, input: number) => {
            console.log(Math[op](input));
        },
        parameters: {
            positional: {
                kind: "tuple",
                parameters: [
                    {
                        brief: "Input number",
                        parse: numberParser,
                    },
                ],
            },
        },
        docs: {
            brief: `Run ${op} on input`,
        },
    });
}

// Create nested route map for math operations
const mathRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        log: buildUnaryMathCommand("log"),
        sqrt: buildUnaryMathCommand("sqrt"),
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Various math operations",
    },
});

// Create root route map with multiple commands
const rootRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        echo: echoCommand, // Assuming echoCommand is defined elsewhere
        math: mathRouteMap,
    },
    aliases: {
        e: "echo",  // Allow 'mycli e "hello"' as shorthand
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "All available commands",
    },
});

// Usage: mycli math sqrt 16  -> outputs 4
// Usage: mycli e "test"      -> outputs "test" (using alias)
```

### Testing > Running the Application

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/testing.mdx

To run a Stricli application, the `run` function takes in the application, the inputs as an array of strings, and the context. If a "mock" version of the context can be constructed, then the application can be tested with the `run` function. At runtime, the `inputs` array is derived from `process.argv`. As such, it has already handled tokenizing the raw inputs and trimming the executable (if present). This means that in order to test `app cmd foo "bar baz"` the inputs array to `run` should be `["cmd", "foo", "bar baz"]`.

